ssion. The interaction between AI POLICY and the AUTHOR ensures that AI integration does not compromise academic integrity. [records: Entities (125), Relationships (101, 121, 145, 148, 144, 135, 124)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"DISCLOSURE as a mechanism for transparency\",\n            \"explanation\": \"DISCLOSURE is a critical mechanism that requires authors to reveal the use of AI tools in their manuscripts, ensuring transparency and accountability. This includes detailing the specific AI tools used, their functions, and the reasons for their application. Publishers such as Emerald, Wiley, and Taylor & Francis have established clear disclosure requirements, often mandating that authors include this information in the methods section, acknowledgment section, or online appendix. The relationship between DISCLOSURE and the AUTHOR underscores the importance of openness in the integration of AI into scholarly work. [records: Entities (21), Relationships (101, 121, 145, 148, 144, 135, 124)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Ethical obligations of AUTHORS regarding AI use\",\n            \"explanation\": \"AUTHORS are ethically obligated to ensure the accuracy, originality, and integrity of their work, even when using AI tools. This includes verifying the reliability of AI-generated content, avoiding plagiarism, and adhering to citation standards. Ethical guidelines from organizations like ASHA and BERA emphasize the need for responsible AI use, while publishers such as BMJ and Springer Nature require authors to maintain the authenticity of their research. The interplay between ETHICAL USE and the AUTHOR highlights the shared responsibility of maintaining academic standards in an AI-integrated environment. [records: Entities (113, 112, 102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Institutional accountability in AI governance\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Institutional accountability is a key aspect of AI governance in academic publishing, with publishers like Elsevier, Emerald, and Wiley enforcing strict policies on AI use. These institutions require authors to disclose AI usage, verify the accuracy of AI-generated content, and ensure that AI tools do not infringe on intellectual property rights. Additionally, journals such as BMJ and Taylor & Francis have specific guidelines that mandate transparency in AI-assisted research, reinforcing the role of institutional frameworks in maintaining academic integrity. [records: Entities (7, 21, 113), Relationships (126, 145, 153, 146, 151, 143, 140, 150, 118, 129)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Impact of AI on authorship and originality\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The integration of AI into academic publishing raises concerns about authorship and originality. While AI tools can assist in tasks such as writing, data analysis, and image generation, they cannot be listed as authors. Authors are responsible for ensuring that AI-generated content is properly cited and that the originality of their work is maintained. Policies from organizations like ICMJE and publishers such as Emerald emphasize that AI should not replace the core intellectual contributions of the author. This relationship between AUTHORSHIP and ORIGINALITY reinforces the need for clear boundaries in AI-assisted research. [records: Entities (134, 102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Challenges in AI disclosure and verification\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Disclosing and verifying AI usage presents significant challenges for authors, particularly in ensuring that all AI-generated content is accurately attributed and verified. Some journals, such as Emerald, require authors to provide specific prompts used with AI tools, while others, like Wiley, mandate that AI-generated content be cited following specific formatting guidelines. The complexity of these requirements highlights the need for standardized disclosure practices across academic publishing platforms. [records: Entities (21, 148, 156), Relationships (101, 121, 145, 148, 144, 135, 124)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Role of peer review in AI governance\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Peer reviewers play a crucial role in AI governance by ensuring that AI usage is disclosed and that the integrity of the research is maintained. Some journals require peer reviewers to disclose the use of AI tools in their evaluations, reinforcing the importance of transparency throughout the publication process. Editors also play a key role in enforcing AI disclosure policies, ensuring that authors adhere to institutional and journal-specific guidelines. This relationship between PEER REVIEW PROCESS and DISCLOSURE highlights the collaborative effort required to uphold academic standards in AI-integrated research. [records: Entities (102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126), Relationships (187, 157, 319)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Legal and ethical implications of AI in publishing\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The use of AI in academic publishing has legal and ethical implications, particularly concerning copyright, privacy, and data security. Authors must ensure that AI tools do not infringe on the rights of others, including copyright holders, and that sensitive data is protected. Policies from organizations like GDPR and publishers such as Taylor & Francis emphasize the need for responsible AI use, including safeguards against data breaches and unauthorized access. These considerations highlight the broader legal and ethical dimensions of AI governance in academic publishing. [records: Entities (119, 123, 128, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126, 145), Relationships (119, 123, 128, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126, 145)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Future directions in AI policy development\",\n            \"explanation\": \"As AI continues to evolve, academic publishing institutions are likely to refine their policies to address emerging challenges. This includes developing more standardized disclosure requirements, enhancing AI detection tools, and promoting greater collaboration between authors, editors, and reviewers. The ongoing dialogue between AI POLICY, DISCLOSURE, and the AUTHOR reflects the dynamic nature of AI governance in academic publishing, with a growing emphasis on transparency, accountability, and ethical responsibility. [records: Entities (125, 21, 113, 102, 101, 10, 1)]\"\n        }\n    ]\n}", "input": "\nYou are an expert in academic publishing and AI policy analysis. You are skilled at interpreting complex regulatory frameworks and identifying key stakeholders and their interactions. You are adept at helping people map out the relationships and structural dynamics within academic publishing ecosystems and AI governance policies.\n\n# Goal\nWrite a comprehensive assessment report of a community taking on the role of a Role: A policy analyst that is examining the intersection of AI tools and academic publishing practices, given a text that outlines specific guidelines, responsibilities, and ethical considerations for authors, editors, and peer reviewers. The report will be used to inform stakeholders about the evolving landscape of AI in scholarly communication and to support the development of more inclusive and transparent policies.. The content of this report includes an overview of the community's key entities and relationships.\n\n# Report Structure\nThe report should include the following sections:\n- TITLE: community's name that represents its key entities - title should be short but specific. When possible, include representative named entities in the title.\n- SUMMARY: An executive summary of the community's overall structure, how its entities are related to each other, and significant points associated with its entities.\n- REPORT RATING: A float score between 0-10 that represents the relevance of the text to academic publishing rules, AI policy compliance, ethical guidelines, and institutional accountability, with 1 being trivial or irrelevant and 10 being highly significant, impactful, and essential for understanding and adhering to academic and AI governance standards.\n- RATING EXPLANATION: Give a single sentence explanation of the rating.\n- DETAILED FINDINGS: A list of 5-10 key insights about the community. Each insight should have a short summary followed by multiple paragraphs of explanatory text grounded according to the grounding rules below. Be comprehensive.\n\nReturn output as a well-formed JSON-formatted string with the following format. Don't use any unnecessary escape sequences. The output should be a single JSON object that can be parsed by json.loads.\n    {\n        \"title\": \"<report_title>\",\n        \"summary\": \"<executive_summary>\",\n        \"rating\": <threat_severity_rating>,\n        \"rating_explanation\": \"<rating_explanation>\"\n        \"findings\": \"[{\"summary\":\"<insight_1_summary>\", \"explanation\": \"<insight_1_explanation\"}, {\"summary\":\"<insight_2_summary>\", \"explanation\": \"<insight_2_explanation\"}]\"\n    }\n\n# Grounding Rules\nAfter each paragraph, add data record reference if the content of the paragraph was derived from one or more data records. Reference is in the format of [records: <record_source> (<record_id_list>, ...<record_source> (<record_id_list>)]. If there are more than 10 data records, show the top 10 most relevant records.\nEach paragraph should contain multiple sentences of explanation and concrete examples with specific named entities. All paragraphs must have these references at the start and end. Use \"NONE\" if there are no related roles or records. Everything should be in English.\n\nExample paragraph with references added:\nThis is a paragraph of the output text [records: Entities (1, 2, 3), Claims (2, 5), Relationships (10, 12)]\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n5,ABILA CITY PARK,Abila City Park is the location of the POK rally\n\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n37,ABILA CITY PARK,POK RALLY,Abila City Park is the location of the POK rally\n38,ABILA CITY PARK,POK,POK is holding a rally in Abila City Park\n39,ABILA CITY PARK,POKRALLY,The POKRally is taking place at Abila City Park\n40,ABILA CITY PARK,CENTRAL BULLETIN,Central Bulletin is reporting on the POK rally taking place in Abila City Park\n\nOutput:\n{\n    \"title\": \"Abila City Park and POK Rally\",\n    \"summary\": \"The community revolves around the Abila City Park, which is the location of the POK rally. The park has relationships with POK, POKRALLY, and Central Bulletin, all\nof which are associated with the rally event.\",\n    \"rating\": 5.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact rating is moderate due to the potential for unrest or conflict during the POK rally.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Abila City Park as the central location\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Abila City Park is the central entity in this community, serving as the location for the POK rally. This park is the common link between all other\nentities, suggesting its significance in the community. The park's association with the rally could potentially lead to issues such as public disorder or conflict, depending on the\nnature of the rally and the reactions it provokes. [records: Entities (5), Relationships (37, 38, 39, 40)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"POK's role in the community\",\n            \"explanation\": \"POK is another key entity in this community, being the organizer of the rally at Abila City Park. The nature of POK and its rally could be a potential\nsource of threat, depending on their objectives and the reactions they provoke. The relationship between POK and the park is crucial in understanding the dynamics of this community.\n[records: Relationships (38)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"POKRALLY as a significant event\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The POKRALLY is a significant event taking place at Abila City Park. This event is a key factor in the community's dynamics and could be a potential\nsource of threat, depending on the nature of the rally and the reactions it provokes. The relationship between the rally and the park is crucial in understanding the dynamics of this\ncommunity. [records: Relationships (39)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Role of Central Bulletin\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Central Bulletin is reporting on the POK rally taking place in Abila City Park. This suggests that the event has attracted media attention, which could\namplify its impact on the community. The role of Central Bulletin could be significant in shaping public perception of the event and the entities involved. [records: Relationships\n(40)]\"\n        }\n    ]\n\n}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n----Reports-----\nid,full_content\r\n9,\"# Author, AI Policy, and Disclosure in Academic Publishing\n\nThe community centers around the AUTHOR, who is subject to a complex network of AI policies, disclosure requirements, and ethical guidelines. Key entities include AI POLICY, DISCLOSURE, and publishers like Elsevier, Emerald, and Wiley. These entities interact through relationships that enforce transparency, accountability, and ethical use of AI in academic publishing.\n\n## AUTHOR as the central figure in AI governance\n\nThe AUTHOR is the primary stakeholder in the academic publishing process, responsible for ensuring the ethical and transparent use of AI tools. This includes disclosing AI usage, verifying the accuracy of AI-generated content, and maintaining the integrity of their work. The AUTHOR's role is defined by a set of responsibilities that align with AI policies and disclosure requirements across major publishers such as Elsevier, Emerald, and Wiley. [records: Entities (7), Relationships (125, 102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118)]\n\n## AI POLICY as a regulatory framework for AI use\n\nAI POLICY serves as a regulatory framework that guides authors on the ethical and transparent use of AI in academic publishing. It mandates that authors disclose the use of AI technologies, including specific tools, their purposes, and the extent of human oversight. These policies are enforced by journals and publishers, such as Elsevier, which require authors to follow strict guidelines on AI use during manuscript preparation and submission. The interaction between AI POLICY and the AUTHOR ensures that AI integration does not compromise academic integrity. [records: Entities (125), Relationships (125, 102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118)]\n\n## DISCLOSURE as a mechanism for transparency\n\nDISCLOSURE is a critical mechanism that requires authors to reveal the use of AI tools in their manuscripts, ensuring transparency and accountability. This includes detailing the specific AI tools used, their functions, and the reasons for their application. Publishers such as Emerald, Wiley, and Taylor & Francis have established clear disclosure requirements, often mandating that authors include this information in the methods section, acknowledgment section, or online appendix. The relationship between DISCLOSURE and the AUTHOR underscores the importance of openness in the integration of AI into scholarly work. [records: Entities (21), Relationships (102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126)]\n\n## Ethical obligations of AUTHORS regarding AI use\n\nAUTHORS are ethically obligated to ensure the accuracy, originality, and integrity of their work, even when using AI tools. This includes verifying the reliability of AI-generated content, avoiding plagiarism, and adhering to citation standards. Ethical guidelines from organizations like ASHA and BERA emphasize the need for responsible AI use, while publishers such as BMJ and Springer Nature require authors to maintain the authenticity of their research. The interplay between ETHICAL USE and the AUTHOR highlights the shared responsibility of maintaining academic standards in an AI-integrated environment. [records: Entities (113, 112, 102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150)]\n\n## Institutional accountability in AI governance\n\nInstitutional accountability is a key aspect of AI governance in academic publishing, with publishers like Elsevier, Emerald, and Wiley enforcing strict policies on AI use. These institutions require authors to disclose AI usage, verify the accuracy of AI-generated content, and ensure that AI tools do not infringe on intellectual property rights. Additionally, journals such as BMJ and Taylor & Francis have specific guidelines that mandate transparency in AI-assisted research, reinforcing the role of institutional frameworks in maintaining academic integrity. [records: Entities (7, 21, 113), Relationships (126, 145, 153, 146, 151, 143, 140, 150, 118, 129)]\n\n## Impact of AI on authorship and originality\n\nThe integration of AI into academic publishing raises concerns about authorship and originality. While AI tools can assist in tasks such as writing, data analysis, and image generation, they cannot be listed as authors. Authors are responsible for ensuring that AI-generated content is properly cited and that the originality of their work is maintained. Policies from organizations like ICMJE and publishers such as Emerald emphasize that AI should not replace the core intellectual contributions of the author. This relationship between AUTHORSHIP and ORIGINALITY reinforces the need for clear boundaries in AI-assisted research. [records: Entities (134, 102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118)]\n\n## Challenges in AI disclosure and verification\n\nDisclosing and verifying AI usage presents significant challenges for authors, particularly in ensuring that all AI-generated content is accurately attributed and verified. Some journals, such as Emerald, require authors to provide specific prompts used with AI tools, while others, like Wiley, mandate that AI-generated content be cited following specific formatting guidelines. The complexity of these requirements highlights the need for standardized disclosure practices across academic publishing platforms. [records: Entities (21, 148, 156), Relationships (102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126)]\n\n## Role of peer review in AI governance\n\nPeer reviewers play a crucial role in AI governance by ensuring that AI usage is disclosed and that the integrity of the research is maintained. Some journals require peer reviewers to disclose the use of AI tools in their evaluations, reinforcing the importance of transparency throughout the publication process. Editors also play a key role in enforcing AI disclosure policies, ensuring that authors adhere to institutional and journal-specific guidelines. This relationship between PEER REVIEW PROCESS and DISCLOSURE highlights the collaborative effort required to uphold academic standards in AI-integrated research. [records: Entities (102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126), Relationships (187, 157, 319)]\n\n## Legal and ethical implications of AI in publishing\n\nThe use of AI in academic publishing has legal and ethical implications, particularly concerning copyright, privacy, and data security. Authors must ensure that AI tools do not infringe on the rights of others, including copyright holders, and that sensitive data is protected. Policies from organizations like GDPR and publishers such as Taylor & Francis emphasize the need for responsible AI use, including safeguards against data breaches and unauthorized access. These considerations highlight the broader legal and ethical dimensions of AI governance in academic publishing. [records: Entities (119, 123, 128, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126, 145), Relationships (119, 123, 128, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126, 145)]\n\n## Future directions in AI policy development\n\nAs AI continues to evolve, academic publishing institutions are likely to refine their policies to address emerging challenges. This includes developing more standardized disclosure requirements, enhancing AI detection tools, and promoting greater collaboration between authors, editors, and reviewers. The ongoing dialogue between AI POLICY, DISCLOSURE, and the AUTHOR reflects the dynamic nature of AI governance in academic publishing, with a growing emphasis on transparency, accountability, and ethical responsibility. [records: Entities (125, 21, 113, 102, 101, 10, 1]\"\r\n\n\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\r\n11,MANUSCRIPT,\"A *MANUSCRIPT* is a written work submitted for publication in a journal or book, which may include content generated or assisted by artificial intelligence (AI) technologies, such as AI-generated text, images, data, or other materials. Depending on the extent of AI involvement, the manuscript must include proper disclosures regarding the use of AI tools during its preparation, review, or editing stages. Some descriptions emphasize that AI-assisted or AI-generated content must be clearly identified and documented to meet the rigorous standards of scientific and scholarly assessment. Additionally, certain policies, such as those outlined by Emerald, require compliance with specific guidelines on AI usage and content creation. The manuscript must also undergo standard editorial processes, including editing and fact-checking, to ensure accuracy and integrity. Overall, the inclusion of AI-generated or AI-assisted content necessitates transparency and adherence to ethical and procedural standards in academic publishing.\",25\r\n117,SPRINGER NATURE,\"Springer Nature is a large academic publisher that plays a significant role in the academic publishing ecosystem. As a major publisher of academic journals and books, it actively monitors developments in artificial intelligence (AI) and regularly updates its policies to address emerging challenges and opportunities related to AI use in publications. The organization has specific policies in place regarding the application of AI in scholarly outputs, reflecting its commitment to maintaining ethical standards and ensuring responsible innovation within the academic community.\",7\r\n62,AI TOOL,\"The \"\"AI TOOL\"\" is a software application or system that employs artificial intelligence to support a range of tasks, including writing, editing, content generation, data analysis, and hypothesis development. These tools are designed to assist users in various academic and professional contexts, with an emphasis on responsible usage. Users are required to disclose their use of AI tools and ensure that they are applied ethically and transparently, particularly in scholarly and research environments where accountability and integrity are paramount. The integration of AI tools into academic workflows raises important considerations regarding authorship, originality, and the role of human oversight in AI-assisted work.\",7\r\n63,IMAGE,\"The entity \"\"IMAGE\"\" refers to visual elements within a manuscript, including pictures, charts, medical imagery, photographs, illustrations, diagrams, and figures. These elements may be created or manipulated using AI-assisted tools, although some descriptions specify that certain types of images cannot be generated or altered using generative AI or large language models (LLMs). The key characteristic of an IMAGE is that it must retain its original information, even if modified through AI tools. The descriptions highlight both the potential for AI involvement in image creation and manipulation, as well as restrictions on the use of such technologies in specific contexts.\",4\r\n119,AI ASSISTED COPY EDITING,\"AI Assisted Copy Editing is a process where artificial intelligence is utilized to enhance the readability and stylistic quality of human-generated texts without modifying the underlying content. This approach leverages AI technologies to support editorial tasks, focusing on improving the flow, coherence, and overall presentation of written material while preserving the original meaning and intent of the author. It represents a growing intersection between academic publishing and AI governance, as the integration of such tools raises important questions about authorship, editorial responsibility, and the role of automation in scholarly communication.\",3\r\n94,ARTISTIC RENDERINGS,\"The entity \"\"ARTISTIC RENDERINGS\"\" refers to visual content created through the use of generative AI tools, including images and other graphical elements. This category encompasses tasks that involve the application of AI in generating artistic or illustrative material, such as cover art or graphical abstracts. Such outputs may require disclosure depending on the context or institutional guidelines, highlighting the growing importance of transparency in the use of AI within academic and creative domains. The integration of AI in producing artistic renderings raises questions about authorship, originality, and ethical considerations in both academic publishing and broader artistic practices.\",2\r\n48,\"AUTHOR(\"\"ENTITY\"\"\",,2\r\n65,AUTHORSHIP RESPONSIBILITY,\"The accountability of authors for the accuracy, integrity, and originality of their work, including the use of AI tools\"\"\",2\r\n12,CONTENT,\"The entity \"\"CONTENT\"\" refers to any material submitted to a journal, including text, audio, video, and other formats, which may involve AI technology. It encompasses the information, text, or data included in a manuscript, which must be verified for originality and accuracy when generated by AI. This includes the material presented in a manuscript, such as text, images, and other forms of media, as well as the text, figures, or other material included in a manuscript, which may be generated by AI and must be disclosed. The definition emphasizes the need for transparency and verification, particularly when AI is involved in the creation of the content.\",3\r\n32,ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS,\"A section of a manuscript where authors may disclose the use of AI tools\"\"\",1\r\n142,AI SIMILARITY INDEX,\"A tool used by journals to detect AI-generated content in manuscripts\"\"\",1\r\n31,METHODS,\"A section of a manuscript where authors describe the methods used, including the use of AI tools\"\"\",1\r\n121,NATURE PORTFOLIO,\"A publisher of academic journals that sets standards for publication, including requirements for editing and fact-checking manuscripts\"\"\",1\r\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\r\n101,AUTHOR,MANUSCRIPT,\"Authors are responsible for the content of their manuscripts, including any AI-generated or AI-assisted elements, and must ensure proper disclosure when submitting manuscripts to journals. This responsibility applies across various stages of manuscript preparation, including writing, editing, and review. The manuscripts may include content generated by AI tools such as large language models (LLMs), and authors are required to document and disclose the use of such technologies in accordance with journal policies, including those of publishers like Emerald and Elsevier. Authors prepare and submit manuscripts for evaluation, adhering to guidelines that mandate transparency regarding AI involvement to maintain academic integrity and compliance.\",84\r\n71,AI TECHNOLOGY,MANUSCRIPT,\"AI TECHNOLOGY and MANUSCRIPT are interconnected through the application of AI in academic writing processes. AI technologies may be used in the production of manuscripts, potentially influencing or generating parts of the content, and such use must be disclosed to ensure transparency and maintain academic integrity. Additionally, AI technology may be 